# Prose-mined Voice Rules

_1970 rule(s) extracted across 1060 section(s)._

Extracted by LLM from hand-written prose sections in `corrections.md`. These rules capture *why* an edit happened, not just *what* changed — richer than diff-mined patterns. promote.py merges this into `learned_patterns.md`; voice skills load that as an anchor.

## 2026-05-06 — Idan, AdaExplore explainer ("What AI Agents Get Wrong About Failure")

### Cap em-dashes at ≤ 3 in pieces ≤ 800 words; convert conversational asides to periods

**Why:** Pulp/social register reads with periods, not em-dashes; dashes dilute when overused
**When:** Short-form blog posts (≤ 800 words) in pulp or social register

**Before:** `…trying again — often with the same broken approach…`
**After:** `…trying again. Often with the same broken approach…`

### Give sharp single-sentence central-frame claims their own paragraph

**Why:** White space sells punchlines; burying a key claim mid-paragraph kills its impact
**When:** Pulp-register blog posts with a central thesis or memorable frame line

**Before:** `The retry loop is the default, and the default is wrong. We notice this at Zerg — so a new paper…`
**After:** `The retry loop is the default, and the default is wrong.

We notice this at Zerg…`

### Keep figure captions ≤ 20 words; use numeric tells when data supports; never restate the body

**Why:** Pulp social captions are billboards, not paragraphs; redundancy with body wastes reader attention
**When:** Any figure/diagram caption in short-form blog or social post

**Before:** `Figure 1 shows the pass rate improvement across three phases of the experiment, rising from 22% to 54% as the model learned to correct itself.`
**After:** `1,178 → 174 → 78. Single-pass correctness: 22% → 54%.`

### Name the baseline whenever citing a speedup or improvement metric

**Why:** Vague baselines are what sharp readers attack; precision is compatible with pulp register
**When:** Any performance claim using 'over baseline', 'vs baseline', or 'than baseline'

**Before:** `3.12× speedup over baseline within 100 steps.`
**After:** `3.12× over PyTorch eager within 100 steps.`

### Use exactly one CTA in the closer; keep the more confident and specific one

**Why:** Two CTAs dilute each other; filler enterprise phrases undercut the post's voice
**When:** Pulp blog post closers with any call to action

**Before:** `We'd love to compare notes — or come argue with us about what should and shouldn't transfer.`
**After:** `Come argue with us about what should and shouldn't transfer.`

### Replace 'competitive with X' / 'comparable to X' / 'in line with X' with a verb-forward claim

**Why:** Pulp register wants verbs; nominal hedges hide the actual result
**When:** Any performance or comparison claim in blog, launch copy, or social

**Before:** `competitive with vendor-optimized code`
**After:** `as fast as vendor-optimized code`

### Route gap-admission / strategic-disclosure lines to a separate 'Strategic disclosure' section, not writing-quality findings

**Why:** Whether to admit a gap is a strategic call for the author/CEO, not a copyedit judgment
**When:** Any review of external-facing copy that contains a 'we don't have X yet' type admission

### When a draft title uses 'What X Gets Wrong About Y' or a curiosity-gap shape, check if a flat declarative version exists in the body or share copy and recommend it as primary

**Why:** Flat declaratives are sharper and more pulp; curiosity-gap titles are a worn-out pattern
**When:** Any blog post or article headline in pulp or social register

**Before:** `What AI Agents Get Wrong About Failure`
**After:** `Most AI Agents Have No Memory`

