## Status legend

### Open with the tension or payoff, not the backstory

**Why:** Readers decide in the first sentence whether to continue; context earns its place only after the hook exists.
**When:** Blog post introductions, email subject lines, launch copy headlines

**Before:** `We've been building this for six months and thinking hard about the problem space before we finally arrived at…`
**After:** `Most analytics tools lie to you. Here's what we built instead.`

### Cut throat-clearing phrases ('I wanted to share', 'I thought it might be worth', 'just a quick note')

**Why:** These phrases signal uncertainty and dilute the authority of what follows.
**When:** Professional emails, outreach messages, any first paragraph

**Before:** `I just wanted to quickly share something I thought might be interesting to you.`
**After:** `Here's something worth your attention.`

### Name the reader's problem before naming your solution

**Why:** People scan for evidence you understand them before they trust you to fix anything.
**When:** Product launch copy, cold outreach, landing page above-the-fold text

**Before:** `Introducing FastPipe — a new way to move data.`
**After:** `Your data pipeline breaks every time the schema changes. FastPipe fixes that.`

### Replace 'very', 'really', and 'quite' with a stronger word or nothing

**Why:** Intensifiers weaken the noun or adjective they modify by signaling it couldn't carry the weight alone.
**When:** All professional writing

**Before:** `This is a really important decision that will have a very significant impact.`
**After:** `This decision will reshape how the team ships.`

### Use active voice; make the agent the subject

**Why:** Passive constructions hide accountability and slow the reader down.
**When:** All professional writing, especially announcements and instructions

**Before:** `Mistakes were made and lessons have been learned by the team.`
**After:** `We made mistakes and learned from them.`

### Shorten sentences that run past two clauses

**Why:** Long multi-clause sentences force the reader to hold too much in working memory at once.
**When:** Blog posts, email body copy, any writing meant to be scanned

**Before:** `We looked at the data, which showed a trend, and decided to act on it, which led to the result we wanted.`
**After:** `The data showed a clear trend. We acted on it. It worked.`

### Pick one call to action per email; remove secondary asks

**Why:** Multiple asks diffuse attention and reduce the chance any single one gets done.
**When:** Outreach emails, follow-up messages, newsletter CTAs

**Before:** `Let me know your thoughts, and also feel free to share with others, and book time if you want to chat.`
**After:** `If this resonates, book 20 minutes here.`

### End with the ask or the next step, not a summary

**Why:** Summaries signal the writer is done; a concrete next step pulls the reader forward.
**When:** Emails, proposals, blog post conclusions

**Before:** `So in summary, we covered X, Y, and Z. Hope this was helpful!`
**After:** `Try it on your next draft and see what changes.`

### Replace jargon with the plain word your audience already uses

**Why:** Borrowed jargon signals you're performing expertise rather than demonstrating it.
**When:** Cross-functional emails, blog posts, any writing for a mixed audience

**Before:** `We need to leverage our core competencies to ideate around the opportunity space.`
**After:** `We should use what we're already good at to find new opportunities.`

### Show the specific number; don't describe the magnitude

**Why:** Vague magnitude words ('significant', 'huge', 'major') are reader-relative; numbers anchor meaning.
**When:** Results announcements, launch copy, investor or stakeholder updates

**Before:** `We saw a significant improvement in load time after the change.`
**After:** `Load time dropped from 4.2 s to 0.9 s.`

### Match sentence length to emotional pace: short for emphasis, longer for texture

**Why:** Monotone sentence length flattens the reading experience and buries your most important points.
**When:** Blog posts, essays, narrative sections of longer emails

**Before:** `The launch went well. People liked it. We hit our goals. It was a good day.`
**After:** `The launch hit every goal we set. But the part I'll remember: a customer emailed within the first hour to say it fixed the exact problem we'd bet on.`

### Delete 'I think' and 'I believe' when the sentence already expresses an opinion

**Why:** Hedging a claim that's already clearly your view signals a lack of conviction.
**When:** Professional emails, blog posts, any first-person opinion writing

**Before:** `I think this is probably the right approach for most teams.`
**After:** `This is the right approach for most teams.`

### Use contractions in conversational registers; drop them in formal ones

**Why:** Contractions calibrate warmth and register; mismatched formality sounds robotic or overly casual.
**When:** Blog posts and outreach (use contractions); legal, board, or compliance writing (avoid them)

**Before:** `We are pleased to announce that we have reached our goal.`
**After:** `We're pleased to announce we hit our goal.`

### State your conclusion first, then support it (inverted pyramid)

**Why:** Busy readers often stop after the first paragraph; burying the conclusion loses them.
**When:** Business emails, memos, analytical blog posts

**Before:** `We reviewed the data, consulted the team, and weighed the tradeoffs… therefore we recommend Option B.`
**After:** `We recommend Option B. Here's why.`

### Cut the word 'just' unless it signals timing or precision

**Why:** 'Just' used as a softener minimizes what you're saying and undermines authority.
**When:** All professional writing, especially requests and recommendations

**Before:** `I just wanted to check in and see if you'd had a chance to review this.`
**After:** `Have you had a chance to review this?`

### Don't apologize for the email's length or your reader's time in the opening

**Why:** Pre-emptive apologies frame the message as an imposition before the reader has formed any view.
**When:** All email writing

**Before:** `Sorry for the long email, I know you're busy, but I wanted to…`
**After:** `Three things I need from you by Thursday:`

### Use second person ('you') to address the reader directly rather than 'users' or 'teams'

**Why:** Generic third-person nouns create distance; 'you' makes the reader feel directly addressed.
**When:** Blog posts, marketing copy, outreach emails

**Before:** `Teams that adopt this approach tend to see better results.`
**After:** `When you adopt this approach, you'll see better results.`

### Break up noun stacks into 'X that does Y' or 'X for Y' constructions

**Why:** Stacked nouns compress meaning until it becomes ambiguous or inaccessible.
**When:** Technical writing, product descriptions, any domain-heavy prose

**Before:** `pipeline execution failure notification system configuration`
**After:** `settings for the system that notifies you when a pipeline fails`

### Vary paragraph length; avoid three or more consecutive same-length paragraphs

**Why:** Uniform paragraph length creates a visual and cognitive rhythm that dulls the reader.
**When:** Blog posts, longer emails, any document over 300 words

### Spell out what 'this' or 'it' refers to when the antecedent is more than one sentence back

**Why:** Ambiguous pronouns force backtracking and break reading flow.
**When:** All writing, especially technical explanations and multi-step arguments

**Before:** `The system processes the event, logs the result, and updates the state. This is why it matters.`
**After:** `The system processes the event, logs the result, and updates the state. That audit trail is why the design matters.`

