## Anti-drift contract

### Prefer verbs over noun-heavy constructions; keep the actor and action visible

**Why:** Nominalizations bury the action and actor, making sentences harder to parse.
**When:** Professional writing where verbs have been converted into abstract nouns (e.g., 'implementation of', 'achievement of')

**Before:** `The implementation of the solution resulted in the achievement of improved performance metrics.`
**After:** `We implemented the fix and performance improved.`

### Never open with a meta-statement about the topic; start with the first substantive sentence

**Why:** Throat-clearing openers delay signal and signal low-effort writing.
**When:** Blog posts, launch copy, and professional emails — any piece with a crafted opener

**Before:** `In today's fast-paced world, effective communication has never been more important.`
**After:** `[Cut the opener entirely; start with the first substantive sentence.]`

### Pick one hedge if uncertainty is needed; never stack qualifiers; default to declarative

**Why:** Stacked hedges drain confidence from claims and obscure meaning.
**When:** Any professional writing where uncertainty needs to be signaled

**Before:** `This solution might potentially be able to help teams that are possibly struggling with…`
**After:** `This solution helps teams that struggle with…`

### In post-mortems and mea-culpa writing, use active voice with an explicit subject

**Why:** Passive voice obscures accountability; readers notice and lose trust.
**When:** Post-mortems, apology emails, incident write-ups

**Before:** `Mistakes were made during the rollout.`
**After:** `We made mistakes during the rollout.`

### Replace adjective stacks with one specific, verifiable claim

**Why:** Generic adjectives signal marketing filler; specific data builds credibility.
**When:** Product or feature descriptions in launch copy, blog posts, and sales writing

**Before:** `Our platform offers robust, enterprise-grade, scalable, and reliable infrastructure.`
**After:** `Our platform scales to enterprise workloads and has maintained 99.9% uptime for two years.`

### In professional cold or warm email, skip pleasantries and open with why you're writing

**Why:** Pleasantries delay the message and read as filler in business contexts.
**When:** Professional cold or warm outreach email

**Before:** `I hope this message finds you well and that you're having a productive week!`
**After:** `[Start with the ask or context on line one.]`

### If an em-dash pair spans more than ~12 words, restructure the sentence instead

**Why:** Long parenthetical interruptions fragment the main clause and lose the reader.
**When:** Any sentence using em-dash pairs in professional writing

**Before:** `The product — which we launched last year, and which has grown steadily — is now profitable.`
**After:** `The product, launched last year, is now profitable. Growth drove it to profitability.`

### In launch copy, skip emotion-performance openers and state the announcement as the lead

**Why:** Phrases like 'excited to announce' are overused and delay the actual news.
**When:** Product launch announcements, press releases, launch emails

**Before:** `We're excited to announce that we're thrilled to share…`
**After:** `[State the announcement directly in the first line.]`

### Never use 'they/it/this' when two or more possible antecedents exist in the preceding sentence

**Why:** Ambiguous pronouns force readers to backtrack and guess the referent.
**When:** Any multi-clause or multi-actor sentence in professional writing

**Before:** `Engineers reviewed the spec with the PMs. They then updated it.`
**After:** `Engineers reviewed the spec with the PMs, who then updated it.`

### All bullets in a list must share the same grammatical form; pick one and enforce it

**Why:** Inconsistent parallel structure creates cognitive friction and looks unpolished.
**When:** Any bulleted or numbered list in blog posts, emails, or launch copy

**Before:** `• Improve latency  • Reducing cost  • Enhanced reliability`
**After:** `• Improve latency  • Reduce cost  • Enhance reliability`

### Follow any jargon term immediately with a plain-English translation or example if the audience may not know it

**Why:** Unexplained jargon excludes readers and signals imprecision.
**When:** Blog posts or copy targeting a mixed or non-specialist audience

**Before:** `We leverage synergistic paradigms to optimize stakeholder outcomes.`
**After:** `We combine approaches that let customers ship faster.`

### Don't join independent clauses with only a comma; use a dash, semicolon, conjunction, or split them

**Why:** Comma splices read as run-ons and signal weak sentence control.
**When:** Any sentence joining two independent clauses in professional writing

**Before:** `The API is fast, it handles 10k req/s.`
**After:** `The API is fast — it handles 10k req/s.`

### In request emails, state the ask in the first sentence, then provide context

**Why:** Leading with context makes recipients read paragraphs before knowing what's needed.
**When:** Professional emails that make a request or need something from the recipient

**Before:** `[Three paragraphs of context] …which is why we're asking for a 30-day extension.`
**After:** `We need a 30-day extension. Here's why: [context]`

### Delete 'very' and 'really' as intensifiers; if the sentence needs them to land, rewrite the claim

**Why:** Weak intensifiers signal an under-supported claim rather than strengthening it.
**When:** All professional writing — blog posts, launch copy, emails

**Before:** `This is a very important update that will really change how teams work.`
**After:** `This update changes how teams work.`

### Within a narrative section, don't switch tenses unless explicitly shifting time frames

**Why:** Tense shifts disorient readers and obscure chronology.
**When:** Retrospective blog posts, case studies, narrative emails

**Before:** `We launched in 2021. The team works through the night. By morning we had shipped.`
**After:** `[Pick one tense — past for retrospectives, present for case studies — and hold it.]`

### Cut or compress transitional sentences longer than ~12 words to a phrase

**Why:** Long transitions stall momentum without adding meaning.
**When:** Blog posts and longer-form writing with section or argument transitions

**Before:** `Having said all of that, and keeping in mind the context we've established above, it's worth considering that…`
**After:** `Given that context:`

