## Status

### Strip solo intensifiers (really, very, truly, quite, just) unless load-bearing

**Why:** Intensifiers signal the writer doesn't trust the noun or adjective to carry the claim, and cutting them strengthens it.
**When:** Any professional writing — emails, blog posts, launch copy

**Before:** `This is a really transformative approach to hiring.`
**After:** `This is a transformative approach to hiring.`

### When you know who acted, name them — rewrite passive constructions into active ones

**Why:** Named agents create accountability and motion; passive constructions create distance.
**When:** Emails and launch copy where ownership matters; acceptable in blog posts when the agent is genuinely unknown or unimportant

**Before:** `The decision was made to delay the rollout.`
**After:** `We decided to delay the rollout.`

### Cut 'it's important to,' 'it's worth noting,' 'needless to say,' 'it should be mentioned' — assert directly

**Why:** These phrases front-load noise, signaling something meaningful is coming without actually saying it.
**When:** All registers; especially common in blog intros and email prefacing

**Before:** `It's worth noting that our approach differs from competitors.`
**After:** `Our approach differs from competitors.`

### Delete 'As you can see,' 'As I mentioned,' 'It goes without saying that,' 'Clearly' — start with the substance

**Why:** These openers add no information; they either condescend or signal poor structure.
**When:** Blog posts, emails, any multi-paragraph writing

**Before:** `As you can see, the data supports a different conclusion.`
**After:** `The data supports a different conclusion.`

### Convert nominalizations back into verbs: 'make a decision → decide,' 'give consideration to → consider,' 'have an impact → impact'

**Why:** Nominalizations bloat sentence length and slow reading; the verb form is almost always tighter and more direct.
**When:** All professional writing

**Before:** `We need to make a determination about the timeline.`
**After:** `We need to determine the timeline.`

### Replace worn clichés and tired metaphors with specific language that earns its place

**Why:** Clichés signal the writer didn't think carefully; specific language signals they did.
**When:** All registers, especially launch copy and blog posts where differentiation matters

**Before:** `This will really move the needle for your team.`
**After:** `Teams cut onboarding time by 40% in the first month.`

### Follow every abstract noun (value, impact, outcomes, results, success) immediately with a concrete referent — what, for whom, by how much

**Why:** Abstractions without referents are unverifiable assertions; concrete specifics let the reader evaluate the claim.
**When:** Launch copy, blog posts, any persuasive writing

**Before:** `This creates real value for your business.`
**After:** `This cuts your support queue by half.`

### Don't label emotions (excited, proud, frustrated) — render the scene or action that caused the emotion

**Why:** Telling the reader what to feel directs rather than invites; the scene creates the feeling more reliably.
**When:** Blog posts, personal anecdotes, narrative emails

**Before:** `I was really excited when the contract closed.`
**After:** `I read the signed PDF three times before I believed it.`

### Keep all items in a list grammatically parallel — same part of speech, same verb form, same syntactic shape

**Why:** Parallelism is a contract with the reader; breaking it creates cognitive friction.
**When:** Any list: bullet points, feature lists, numbered steps, series in a sentence

**Before:** `Fast onboarding, Reduces churn, Security built in.`
**After:** `Fast onboarding, lower churn, built-in security.`

### Vary sentence length deliberately — after two or three medium sentences, use a short one, then expand again

**Why:** Uniform sentence length creates a metronome effect that reads as monotone; variation creates emphasis and pace.
**When:** Blog posts, long-form emails, any writing meant to hold attention

**Before:** `We built the tool over six months. The team worked across three time zones. Every sprint taught us something new.`
**After:** `We built the tool over six months, working across three time zones. Every sprint taught us something new.`

### Pick a tense and hold it — only shift intentionally (e.g., past for the story, present for the takeaway)

**Why:** Unintentional tense drift signals the writer wasn't tracking the narrative plane and erodes trust.
**When:** Case studies, blog posts, any narrative writing

**Before:** `We launched in Q3. The team builds quickly. We were surprised by the response.`
**After:** `We launched in Q3. The team built quickly. We were surprised by the response.`

### Every pronoun must have an unambiguous antecedent in the same paragraph — when in doubt, repeat the noun

**Why:** Pronoun ambiguity forces re-reading; clarity costs one extra word.
**When:** All writing; critical in technical or process descriptions with multiple nouns

**Before:** `The platform integrates with the CRM. It then syncs the data. It flags errors automatically.`
**After:** `The platform integrates with the CRM, syncs the data, and flags errors automatically.`

### Lead with the most important information — move context, background, or qualifications after the core claim

**Why:** Readers scan; if the news is buried, most won't reach it.
**When:** Emails, blog posts, announcements; less rigid in long-form narrative where buildup is intentional

**Before:** `Over the past year we've been talking to hundreds of customers… [3 paragraphs]… Today we're launching X.`
**After:** `Today we're launching X. Here's what led us here.`

### Use em dashes sparingly — one, maybe two per page; when reaching for a third, restructure the sentence

**Why:** The em dash's power comes from rarity; overuse flattens it into visual noise.
**When:** Blog posts, long-form copy; less of a concern in short emails

**Before:** `The product — which we built over six months — solves a problem — one we kept hearing about — in a new way.`
**After:** `The product, built over six months, solves a problem we kept hearing about — in a new way.`

### Always use the Oxford (serial) comma in lists of three or more items

**Why:** Omitting it creates genuine ambiguity in some constructions; consistency eliminates the need to judge each case.
**When:** All writing

**Before:** `speed, accuracy and reliability`
**After:** `speed, accuracy, and reliability`

### Cut redundant phrasing where one word contains the meaning of the other: 'past history → history,' 'end result → result,' 'completely finished → finished'

**Why:** Redundancy signals inattention; cutting it tightens prose and signals care.
**When:** All writing

**Before:** `Our past history with this client made us cautious.`
**After:** `Our history with this client made us cautious.`

### Replace jargon and buzzwords with plain-language equivalents — if the plain version sounds weaker, the original claim was weak

**Why:** Buzzwords borrow credibility they haven't earned; plain language forces the writer to earn it.
**When:** All professional writing; especially damaging in external-facing copy

**Before:** `We leverage synergies across the ecosystem to deliver paradigm-shifting outcomes.`
**After:** `We combine our tools' strengths to deliver results no single tool could.`

### Don't open a paragraph with a hedge or concession unless the paragraph's purpose is to resolve a tension — lead with the claim

**Why:** Opening with a hedge teaches readers to skip your first sentence and buries the actual argument.
**When:** Blog posts, persuasive emails, op-ed-style writing

**Before:** `While it's true that this approach has risks, we believe the upside justifies them.`
**After:** `The upside justifies the risk. Here's why.`

### Break sentences longer than ~35 words at the natural seam (usually a conjunction or relative clause)

**Why:** Long sentences tax working memory; splitting creates two opportunities for the reader to anchor.
**When:** All writing

**Before:** `We built this feature because customers said existing tools required too many manual steps and didn't integrate with systems they already used, which meant double work.`
**After:** `We built this feature because customers told us existing tools required too many manual steps. None integrated with systems teams already used, so every task meant double work.`

### Replace a weak verb + adverb with a single strong verb: 'walked slowly → shuffled,' 'spoke loudly → bellowed,' 'moved quickly → sprinted'

**Why:** Strong verbs are more precise and more vivid; adverbs compensate for imprecision.
**When:** Blog posts, narrative emails, any writing where vividness matters; less critical in functional or process writing

**Before:** `He walked slowly to the front of the room.`
**After:** `He shuffled to the front of the room.`

