## Product status guidance

### Open with the sharpest version of your claim, not a windup

**Why:** Readers decide within the first sentence whether to keep reading; burying the point wastes that moment.
**When:** Blog post introductions, email subject lines, and any opening paragraph in professional writing

**Before:** `Over the past few years, a lot of teams have started thinking about how they manage their work.`
**After:** `Most teams are managing work in three tools when one would do.`

### Cut throat-clearing phrases like 'I think,' 'I believe,' and 'In my opinion'

**Why:** They dilute authority; the reader already knows the prose represents your view.
**When:** Any first-person professional writing — blog posts, essays, launch copy, emails

**Before:** `I think this is one of the more important shifts happening in productivity software.`
**After:** `This is one of the more important shifts happening in productivity software.`

### Replace vague intensifiers ('really,' 'very,' 'quite') with a specific detail or delete them

**Why:** Vague intensifiers signal the writer hasn't found the concrete fact that would do the work.
**When:** All registers — blog, email, launch copy

**Before:** `It's really fast and quite easy to get started.`
**After:** `It's fast — most teams are set up in under ten minutes.`

### Use active voice; rewrite passive constructions to name the actor

**Why:** Active voice is shorter, clearer, and more direct about who is doing what.
**When:** All professional writing registers, especially launch copy and email

**Before:** `Decisions were made faster by teams using the integration.`
**After:** `Teams using the integration made decisions faster.`

### Prefer short, concrete Anglo-Saxon words over Latinate abstractions

**Why:** Plain words are processed faster and land harder; abstractions create distance.
**When:** Blog posts and emails — anywhere you want directness

**Before:** `We are facilitating the optimization of cross-functional collaboration.`
**After:** `We help teams work better together.`

### End sections and emails on action or implication, not a restatement of what was just said

**Why:** Restatements feel like padding; a forward-looking close gives the reader something to do or think.
**When:** Email closings, blog post section endings, any paragraph-final sentence

**Before:** `So that's why we built this feature. We hope you find it useful.`
**After:** `Try it on your next planning cycle and see if it cuts the prep time.`

### Use em-dashes for sharp asides; don't overload parentheses or comma pairs for the same job

**Why:** Em-dashes create rhythm and signal importance; parentheses visually bury the aside.
**When:** Blog posts and long-form emails where rhythm matters

**Before:** `The new view (which launched last week) pulls in data from all connected apps.`
**After:** `The new view — launched last week — pulls in data from all connected apps.`

### Name the specific product or feature rather than gesturing at 'the platform' or 'the solution'

**Why:** Specificity builds credibility and makes copy scannable; generic nouns erode both.
**When:** Launch copy, product emails, blog posts about specific features

**Before:** `Our solution helps you stay on top of everything in one place.`
**After:** `Zergboard surfaces every open task, deadline, and blocker in one view.`

### Quantify claims when you have the number; remove the claim if you don't

**Why:** Unquantified superlatives ('the fastest,' 'dramatically faster') read as marketing filler without data.
**When:** Launch copy, case-study writing, product emails making performance claims

**Before:** `Teams save a dramatic amount of time with the new workflow.`
**After:** `Teams running the new workflow report cutting weekly status prep from 45 minutes to 10.`

### Keep paragraphs to three sentences or fewer in email and launch copy

**Why:** Dense paragraphs raise abandonment; short blocks signal that each idea is complete and scannable.
**When:** Emails and launch copy; also useful for blog post body paragraphs

### Don't hedge shipping claims — only claim something is live if it is fully shipped to all users

**Why:** Overstating availability erodes trust when readers try to find a feature that isn't there.
**When:** Launch emails, product blog posts, any copy describing ZergStack product availability

**Before:** `ZergStack now connects your calendar, meetings, mail, and CRM in one place.`
**After:** `Zergboard and ZergCal are live and deeply connected; more integrations are on the way.`

### Use second person ('you') to address the reader directly; avoid the distancing third person ('users,' 'teams') when speaking to the reader

**Why:** Second person creates immediacy and makes the benefit feel personal rather than abstract.
**When:** Launch copy, onboarding emails, and any copy aimed at the end user

**Before:** `Users can see all their tasks without switching between apps.`
**After:** `You can see all your tasks without switching between apps.`

### Cut the setup clause and lead with the verb when the subject is obvious

**Why:** Front-loaded setup clauses delay the action and bleed energy from the sentence.
**When:** Bullet points, email openings, and any sentence where the subject is the product or the reader

**Before:** `With Zergboard, you are able to track every open item across your stack.`
**After:** `Track every open item across your stack in Zergboard.`

### Use present tense for product descriptions; reserve past tense for historical narrative

**Why:** Present tense makes product copy feel alive and immediate; past tense implies the feature is dated.
**When:** Product blog posts, launch copy, feature descriptions

**Before:** `The new dashboard gave users a single view of all connected apps.`
**After:** `The new dashboard gives you a single view of all connected apps.`

### When listing features, use parallel grammatical structure across all items

**Why:** Non-parallel lists force the reader to re-parse each item; parallel structure lets them scan.
**When:** Bullet lists in emails, blog posts, and landing copy

**Before:** `– Real-time sync
– You can assign tasks
– Integrated with your calendar`
**After:** `– Real-time sync
– Task assignment
– Calendar integration`

### Avoid the word 'leverage' as a verb; use 'use,' 'apply,' or 'tap' instead

**Why:** 'Leverage' as a verb is overused business jargon that signals corporate distance, not clarity.
**When:** All professional writing registers

**Before:** `Teams can leverage the integration to streamline their workflows.`
**After:** `Teams can use the integration to cut handoff time.`

### Avoid 'seamless,' 'robust,' 'powerful,' and 'intuitive' — show the quality instead

**Why:** These adjectives have been drained of meaning by overuse; showing the quality is always more persuasive.
**When:** Launch copy, product emails, marketing blog posts

**Before:** `A seamless and powerful integration that's intuitive for any team.`
**After:** `Set up in minutes; no IT ticket required.`

### Write CTAs as specific actions, not vague invitations

**Why:** Specific CTAs reduce friction by telling the reader exactly what happens when they click.
**When:** Email CTAs, blog post CTAs, landing page buttons

**Before:** `Learn more`
**After:** `See how Zergboard works`

### When editing for tone, preserve the writer's sentence rhythm and characteristic moves; change words, not cadence

**Why:** Ghostwriting that flattens the original voice produces copy the author won't recognize as theirs.
**When:** Any collaborative editing or ghostwriting of Matt's blog posts or emails

### Avoid starting consecutive sentences with the same word or construction

**Why:** Repeated sentence openings create monotony that signals low editing effort to close readers.
**When:** Blog posts and longer emails — anywhere three or more sentences appear in sequence

**Before:** `We built this for teams. We wanted to make it fast. We also wanted it to be simple.`
**After:** `We built this for teams who needed speed — and didn't want to sacrifice simplicity to get it.`

