## Products

### Open with the concrete thing that happened, not a throat-clearing setup

**Why:** Readers decide in the first sentence whether to keep going; burying the news loses them
**When:** Blog post and email openings

**Before:** `There's been a lot of discussion lately about how AI is changing work. I wanted to share some thoughts.`
**After:** `Last week an agent on our team filed, prioritized, and closed 40 tickets without a human touching the queue.`

### Name the specific product or feature, not the category

**Why:** Vague category language ('our AI tools') diffuses impact; named specifics build credibility
**When:** Any copy mentioning Zerg products — launch emails, blog posts, product descriptions

**Before:** `Our AI-powered project management tools help teams move faster.`
**After:** `Zergboard lets agents file, move, comment on, and close work alongside humans.`

### Cut 'we believe' and 'we think' — state the claim directly

**Why:** Hedging with belief verbs signals uncertainty and weakens the argument
**When:** Product copy, launch emails, blog posts making a product or market claim

**Before:** `We believe the future of work includes AI agents as full participants.`
**After:** `The future of work includes AI agents as full participants.`

### Use the second person ('you', 'your team') instead of 'teams' or 'users'

**Why:** Second person creates direct address and makes the benefit feel personal
**When:** Marketing copy, email subject lines, CTAs, and launch announcements

**Before:** `Teams can finally give agents real work to do.`
**After:** `You can finally give agents real work to do.`

### Put the verb before the noun phrase in benefit statements

**Why:** Front-loading action keeps sentences driving forward instead of stalling on noun piles
**When:** Feature bullets, benefit lists, and landing page copy

**Before:** `Agent-readable availability and follow-up workflow support is included.`
**After:** `Schedule meetings, track availability, and trigger follow-ups — all agent-readable.`

### Replace '-powered' compounds ('AI-powered', 'agent-powered') with active verb phrases

**Why:** '-powered' is filler that adds no information; verbs show what the product actually does
**When:** Any product description, headline, or tagline

**Before:** `AI-powered scheduling for modern teams.`
**After:** `Scheduling that agents can read, write, and act on.`

### Avoid 'seamlessly' and 'effortlessly' — show the mechanism instead

**Why:** Adverbs like 'seamlessly' are meaningless without evidence; the mechanism is the proof
**When:** Feature descriptions, product copy, onboarding emails

**Before:** `Agents integrate seamlessly into your existing workflows.`
**After:** `Agents pick up tasks from the same board your team uses — no separate queue.`

### End sections with a forward-pointing sentence, not a summary restatement

**Why:** Restatements feel like filler; a forward hook gives the reader a reason to continue
**When:** Blog post section endings, multi-section emails

**Before:** `That's why we built Zergboard the way we did.`
**After:** `That's the pattern we kept returning to as we built the rest of the stack.`

### Use short declarative sentences for key claims; reserve complex sentences for explanation

**Why:** Short sentences land punches; long sentences bury them
**When:** Headlines, opening paragraphs, and CTAs across all copy types

**Before:** `Because agents need to interact with work management tools in the same way that humans do, we built Zergboard.`
**After:** `Agents need to do work, not watch it. That's why we built Zergboard.`

### Use 'human + agent' (with a plus sign) as the consistent phrasing for mixed teams, not 'human-AI'

**Why:** Consistent terminology reinforces the Zerg brand framing; 'human-AI' is generic
**When:** All product copy, blog posts, and emails that describe the team composition Zerg is built for

**Before:** `Built for human-AI collaboration.`
**After:** `Built for human + agent teams.`

### Avoid 'solution' and 'solutions' as product nouns unless referring specifically to Zerg Solutions

**Why:** 'Solution' is enterprise filler with no concrete meaning; it obscures what the product does
**When:** Product descriptions, headlines, and benefit copy across all surfaces

**Before:** `A complete solution for AI-first teams.`
**After:** `A stack built for teams running agents alongside humans.`

### When listing products or features, lead with what ships first or what's most concrete

**Why:** Leading with shipped things builds credibility; leading with roadmap items undercuts it
**When:** Launch emails, product announcements, and feature list copy

**Before:** `ZergStack includes ZergMail, ZergMeeting, ZergChat, ZergCal, and Zergboard.`
**After:** `Start with Zergboard and ZergCal — both shipped. ZergMeeting, ZergChat, and ZergMail are staged.`

### Describe what agents can do as first-class actors, not as add-ons to human workflows

**Why:** Framing agents as add-ons positions Zerg as an automation tool; framing them as first-class actors is the differentiator
**When:** Any copy describing agent capabilities in Zerg products

**Before:** `ZergChat lets you add agents to conversations to help your team.`
**After:** `In ZergChat, agents send and receive messages, get @-mentioned, and respond — the same way humans do.`

### Use 'fixed-fee' not 'flat-rate' or 'fixed-price' when describing Zerg Solutions pricing

**Why:** Consistent terminology across channels reduces buyer confusion
**When:** Any copy referencing Zerg Solutions engagements

**Before:** `Flat-rate custom software builds for AI-first teams.`
**After:** `Fixed-fee custom software workstreams for AI-first teams.`

### Do not qualify availability status inline in marketing copy; handle it in footnotes or a separate section

**Why:** Inline status hedges ('preview', 'coming soon') break reading flow and dilute confidence
**When:** Marketing emails, launch posts, and landing page copy

**Before:** `ZergMeeting (currently in preview) turns transcripts into work items.`
**After:** `ZergMeeting turns transcripts and decisions into work items. (See availability notes below.)`

### Prefer 'turns X into Y' over 'helps you X' for transformation features

**Why:** 'Helps you' is weak agency; 'turns X into Y' names the concrete transformation
**When:** Feature descriptions for ZergMeeting, Zergboard, and any pipeline-style feature

**Before:** `ZergMeeting helps you capture decisions and create follow-up tasks.`
**After:** `ZergMeeting turns transcripts and decisions into work items.`

### Never use 'bolted on' to describe a competitor's approach unless quoting a customer

**Why:** Using pejorative framing unprompted sounds defensive; it lands better as a customer quote or implicit contrast
**When:** Competitive positioning copy, product descriptions for ZergChat

**Before:** `Unlike other tools that bolt agents on through webhook bots, ZergChat treats them as first-class.`
**After:** `In ZergChat, agents participate the way humans do — messages, @-mentions, and replies — not through webhook bots tacked on after the fact.`

### Reference ZTC as the shared layer, not as a feature or product

**Why:** Calling ZTC a feature confuses buyers; it's infrastructure, not a selling point on its own
**When:** Technical blog posts, architecture explanations, and any copy that needs to mention ZTC

**Before:** `ZTC is our powerful shared agent runtime that ties everything together.`
**After:** `ZTC is the shared agent and runtime layer that runs behind the full stack.`

