## Products

### Never open with a generic setup phrase; start with the specific claim or contrast

**Why:** Throat-clearing openers delay the point and signal generic thinking
**When:** Opening sentences of blog posts, emails, and launch copy

**Before:** `In today's fast-paced world, every team needs tools that can keep up.`
**After:** `Most project tools weren't built for agents. Zergboard was.`

### Remove hedging qualifiers (might, potentially, could be, perhaps) unless the uncertainty is meaningful

**Why:** Hedges make claims feel tentative and reduce persuasive force
**When:** Any descriptive or positioning copy

**Before:** `This might be useful for teams that are potentially thinking about integrating AI agents.`
**After:** `This is for teams already running agents — or about to.`

### Turn nominalizations back into verbs

**Why:** Nominalized sentences feel bureaucratic and slow
**When:** Any prose — especially technical or product descriptions

**Before:** `The implementation of agent scheduling requires consideration of availability windows.`
**After:** `To schedule agents, you need to know when they're available.`

### Split sentences that chain more than two ideas with commas or conjunctions

**Why:** Each sentence should carry one main idea
**When:** Any long compound sentence in blog posts or copy

**Before:** `Agents can read the board, pick up tasks, update statuses, and close work items without being prompted, which means your team can stay focused on higher-leverage decisions.`
**After:** `Agents read the board, pick up tasks, and close work items on their own. Your team stays focused on higher-leverage decisions.`

### Cut filler transitions ('with that in mind,' 'let's take a look at,' 'in practice')

**Why:** They add length without adding meaning
**When:** Transitions between sections or ideas in any piece

**Before:** `So, with all of that in mind, let's take a look at how this actually works in practice.`
**After:** `Here's how it works.`

### Strip performative excitement from announcements; let the news carry the weight

**Why:** Enthusiasm signaling reads as hollow and dilutes the announcement itself
**When:** Product launch announcements, release emails, changelog posts

**Before:** `We're incredibly excited to announce that ZergCal is officially live!`
**After:** `ZergCal is live.`

### Don't frame product copy as a moral mission; state the functional problem being solved

**Why:** Moralizing feels preachy and lets readers draw their own conclusions
**When:** Product descriptions, About pages, launch emails

**Before:** `In a world where burnout is rampant, we believe every worker deserves tools that respect their time.`
**After:** `Teams running agents don't need another tool designed for purely-human workflows.`

### Address the reader directly as 'you' and describe a specific situation they'd recognize

**Why:** Writing to a category feels impersonal; writing to a situation creates recognition
**When:** All professional copy and emails

**Before:** `For teams looking to scale their operations, ZergStack offers a comprehensive suite of solutions.`
**After:** `If you're running agents and humans on the same work queue, ZergStack is built for that.`

### When you have three or more adjectives or buzzwords in a row, replace them with what the thing actually does

**Why:** Buzzword stacking signals avoidance of a real description
**When:** Taglines, hero copy, product descriptions

**Before:** `A next-generation, AI-powered, end-to-end workflow automation platform for the modern enterprise.`
**After:** `Project management built for teams where agents and humans share the same board.`

### Don't use forced-informal openers ('hey there,' 'just wanted to,' 'super exciting'); be direct and specific instead

**Why:** Casual signaling words read as fake; real informality comes from directness
**When:** Emails, update posts, any copy attempting a friendly register

**Before:** `Hey there! Just wanted to pop in and share some super exciting news with you all!`
**After:** `Quick update:`

### Lead with the conclusion, then back it up

**Why:** Burying the point in preamble makes readers work to find the value
**When:** Blog posts, long-form emails, any piece with a narrative setup

**Before:** `After months of working with AI-first teams and iterating on workflows, we've arrived at principles that we think can help...`
**After:** `Here's what we've learned about running agents alongside humans.`

### Make all items in a list grammatically parallel

**Why:** Mixed grammatical forms in a list read as sloppy
**When:** Any bulleted or inline list

**Before:** `Zergboard helps with: managing tasks, agent coordination, and it makes it easier to track completions.`
**After:** `Zergboard handles task management, agent coordination, and completion tracking.`

### Don't use rhetorical questions as section headers; use a noun phrase or declarative title instead

**Why:** Rhetorical question headers are weak and carry less information than a direct title
**When:** Blog post and article section headers

**Before:** `Why Does Agent Scheduling Matter?`
**After:** `Agent Scheduling  or  Why Agent Scheduling Is Harder Than It Looks`

### Don't announce what you're about to say and then say it; collapse the announce and content into one move

**Why:** Double-announcing wastes words and delays the reader
**When:** Introductions to lists, section openers, any 'I'm going to tell you X' construction

**Before:** `In this post, I'm going to walk you through three key strategies. The three strategies are: ...`
**After:** `Three strategies for deploying agents on a shared board:`

### End on an action, a specific product, or a concrete next step — not vague optimism

**Why:** Closing with sentiment is a missed CTA
**When:** Closing paragraphs of blog posts, emails, and launch copy

**Before:** `We're excited about what the future holds and can't wait to see what you build.`
**After:** `If you're running a team with agents, try Zergboard — it's free to start.`

### Replace 'leverage' (as a verb) with the actual verb being described

**Why:** 'Leverage' as a verb is consultant-speak that obscures the real action
**When:** Any copy describing what users or teams do with the product

**Before:** `Teams can leverage ZergStack to streamline their workflows.`
**After:** `Teams use ZergStack to run agents and humans on the same work queue.`

### Replace 'seamless' and 'frictionless' with a description of what actually makes it smooth

**Why:** These words are empty claims without a mechanism behind them
**When:** Product descriptions and feature copy

**Before:** `ZergCal offers a seamless scheduling experience for agents and humans alike.`
**After:** `ZergCal gives agents readable availability windows and handles follow-up automatically.`

### Don't use 'solutions' as a standalone noun; name the actual thing being built or sold

**Why:** 'Solutions' on its own conveys no information about the product
**When:** Company and product descriptions, homepage copy

**Before:** `We build solutions for AI-first teams.`
**After:** `We build scheduling tools, boards, and comms layers for teams running agents.`

### Replace 'journey' and 'space' (as in 'in the X space') with concrete nouns and verbs

**Why:** These are category-speak that avoid saying anything specific
**When:** Market positioning copy, blog posts, any framing of the competitive landscape

**Before:** `In the AI agent space, every team is on its own journey toward automation.`
**After:** `Every team deploys agents differently.`

### Replace 'robust' with a list of the actual features or capabilities

**Why:** 'Robust' signals you haven't specified what the features are
**When:** Feature descriptions and product copy

**Before:** `Zergboard comes with a robust set of features for agent task management.`
**After:** `Zergboard lets agents file, move, comment on, and close work items.`

### Replace 'empower' and 'enable' with the direct action the product performs

**Why:** These verbs are passive-voice in disguise and obscure what the product actually does
**When:** Product positioning and feature copy

**Before:** `ZergStack empowers teams to deploy agents at scale.`
**After:** `ZergStack is built so agents and humans can work from the same board.`

### Replace technology superlatives ('cutting-edge,' 'state-of-the-art') with the actual mechanism or capability

**Why:** Superlatives are filler; the mechanism is the real claim
**When:** Technical product descriptions and launch copy

**Before:** `Our cutting-edge platform uses state-of-the-art AI to transform how your team works.`
**After:** `ZTC gives agents a shared runtime so they can file tickets and update statuses without custom glue code.`

### Replace 'transform' and 'revolutionize' with a description of what specifically changes

**Why:** These words are unearned promises without a concrete before/after
**When:** Product positioning and launch copy

**Before:** `ZergStack will transform the way your team collaborates.`
**After:** `ZergStack lets agents and humans work from the same queue, board, and inbox.`

### In first-person copy, don't shift to third person to refer to yourself; stay in 'I' or 'we'

**Why:** Third-person self-reference in first-person copy breaks the narrative voice
**When:** Blog posts, emails, any first-person professional writing

**Before:** `Matt and the team at Zerg have spent months on this. He believes...`
**After:** `We've spent months thinking about how agents work alongside humans. Here's what we've found.`

### Don't mix conversational and formal/academic register within a single piece

**Why:** Register shifts break the reader's sense of a consistent voice
**When:** Any piece mixing casual constructions with phrases like 'furthermore,' 'non-trivial,' or 'implications'

**Before:** `Here's the thing: teams need better tooling. Furthermore, the implications for organizational agility are non-trivial.`
**After:** `Here's the thing: teams need better tooling. The consequences aren't small.`

### Use 'we' when speaking as the company; use 'I' only in explicitly personal contexts such as founder stories or personal blog posts

**Why:** Mixing pronouns creates ambiguity about whether the voice is personal or institutional
**When:** Any piece that could be read as either company communication or personal writing

**Before:** `I built ZergStack for teams running agents and humans together.`
**After:** `We built ZergStack for teams running agents and humans together.`

### Use present tense throughout product copy; don't mix present and future tense when describing existing features

**Why:** Tense inconsistency signals that features may not yet exist or may be half-shipped
**When:** Feature descriptions and product copy for live products

**Before:** `Zergboard tracks tasks. Agents will be able to file and close tickets. The board updates in real time.`
**After:** `Zergboard tracks tasks. Agents file and close tickets. The board updates in real time.`

### In feature descriptions, make the agent or user the grammatical subject rather than using passive voice

**Why:** Passive voice obscures who does what and weakens the description
**When:** Feature bullet points and product copy

**Before:** `Tasks can be filed by agents, and status updates are sent automatically.`
**After:** `Agents file tasks and send status updates automatically.`

### Replace 'all kinds of,' 'various,' and 'a wide range of' with the actual target or situation

**Why:** Vague scope words are scope-dodges that avoid committing to a real audience
**When:** Audience and positioning copy

**Before:** `Zergboard works great for all kinds of teams.`
**After:** `Zergboard is for teams where agents and humans share the same work queue.`

### When you have a real number, use it instead of 'several' or 'many'

**Why:** Vague quantity words weaken credibility when a real number is available
**When:** Social proof, case study references, and any quantified claim

**Before:** `We've worked with several companies deploying agents at scale.`
**After:** `We've worked with 12 teams deploying agents on shared work queues.`

### Describe what the product actually does (mechanism), not the outcome it produces

**Why:** Outcome claims are weak without the mechanism that produces them
**When:** Feature descriptions and product copy

**Before:** `ZergCal makes scheduling easier for everyone.`
**After:** `ZergCal exposes availability windows agents can read directly and handles follow-up workflows automatically.`

### Replace abstract benefit phrases ('move faster,' 'work smarter') with the specific cost or friction being removed

**Why:** Generic benefit claims carry no information and read as clichés
**When:** Value proposition copy, hero headlines, email subject lines

**Before:** `ZergStack helps teams move faster and work smarter.`
**After:** `ZergStack cuts the coordination overhead of running agents and humans on the same team.`

### Don't close with a vision statement; end with what exists now or what the reader can do right now

**Why:** Closing with a future vision sounds like a VC pitch and leaves the reader with nothing to act on
**When:** Closing paragraphs of blog posts, launch emails, and product pages

**Before:** `We're building toward a future where human and AI collaboration is seamless and natural.`
**After:** `ZergStack handles the plumbing so agents can actually work alongside humans — same board, same inbox, same queue.`

