## Best-fit customers

### Start with the claim, not the setup

**Why:** Announcing what you're about to say delays the point and signals weak confidence in the idea itself.
**When:** Opening sentences of sections or paragraphs in blog posts, emails, and launch copy

**Before:** `In this section, I'm going to explain why most task managers fail AI teams...`
**After:** `Most task managers fail AI teams because they were built for humans who decide.`

### Open on something specific and true — cut warm-up first sentences

**Why:** The first sentence earns its place or it gets cut; generic scene-setting loses readers immediately.
**When:** Opening lines of any professional writing piece

**Before:** `There's a lot of talk these days about AI agents...`
**After:** `AI agents don't wait for permission.`

### Drop hedges from strong claims — say the thing plainly

**Why:** Qualifiers don't make claims sound careful; they make them sound unconvinced.
**When:** Any sentence making a directional or comparative claim in blog posts or launch copy

**Before:** `AI agents might be one of the more significant shifts in how software gets built.`
**After:** `AI agents are the biggest shift in software since the cloud.`

### Split long sentences to land the key insight in its own short sentence

**Why:** Short sentences make claims hit harder; burying insight inside length dilutes impact.
**When:** Sentences carrying a central claim or conclusion in any professional writing

**Before:** `One of the things that makes this approach particularly effective is that it doesn't require the user to understand the underlying logic of the system.`
**After:** `The user doesn't need to understand the system. That's the whole point.`

### Describe the behavior, not a label for how impressive it is

**Why:** Labeling something remarkable tells the reader what to think; showing what it does lets it land on its own.
**When:** Writing about product capabilities or technical achievements in any register

**Before:** `This is a remarkable capability that sets the system apart.`
**After:** `The agent rewrites its own task list when the goal changes mid-run.`

### Name the actor — avoid passive voice that hides who does what

**Why:** Every action has an actor; hiding it makes prose vague and corporate.
**When:** Any sentence describing system behavior, decisions, or processes

**Before:** `Decisions are made based on the current state of the system.`
**After:** `The agent decides based on what it knows right now.`

### Delete filler transitions; write one only if it adds information

**Why:** Transitions that carry no meaning are seam-hiders, not bridges — they signal the writer lost the thread.
**When:** Between paragraphs or sections in blog posts and long-form emails

**Before:** `With that in mind, let's turn to... / Having said that... / As we've seen...`

### End on the sharpest point — don't summarize what was just said

**Why:** A trailing summary describes the point instead of being the point, which weakens the ending.
**When:** Closing sentences of sections or full pieces in blog posts and launch copy

**Before:** `So, as you can see, the agent architecture approach offers several important advantages.`

### Lead with outcome, not a list of features

**Why:** Feature lists tell the reader what a system can do; outcomes tell them what it means for them.
**When:** Product and capability descriptions in launch copy, emails, and blog posts

**Before:** `The system supports task creation, deadline tracking, integration with existing tools, and intelligent reprioritization.`
**After:** `Your backlog stays coherent even when the plan changes mid-sprint — the agent handles reprioritization.`

### Cut intensifiers (very, really, truly, actually) and rewrite the underlying sentence if needed

**Why:** Intensifiers signal weak prose; if the sentence needs one to land, the noun or verb is wrong.
**When:** Any sentence in professional writing, especially claims and value statements

**Before:** `This is a really important distinction. It's truly remarkable what the system can do.`
**After:** `This distinction changes how you build.`

### Lead with the verb — don't bury it behind a long subject clause

**Why:** When the verb hides, the sentence loses energy; subject → verb → object is the natural reading order.
**When:** Any sentence with a complex or extended subject phrase

**Before:** `The way in which most task management tools have been designed fundamentally limits their usefulness for AI-native teams.`
**After:** `Most task managers were built for humans. That makes them useless for AI teams.`

### Write in the register of the intended audience, not the register that sounds impressive

**Why:** Academic or consultant-speak creates distance with operators and founders who use plain, direct language.
**When:** Any copy targeting startup operators, founders, or engineering leads

**Before:** `This solution represents a paradigm shift in operational workflow optimization.`
**After:** `Your ops team will stop living in Slack threads.`

### Delete framework citations and say the actual insight instead

**Why:** Name-checking a concept performs knowledge rather than using it; the idea matters, not the attribution.
**When:** Blog posts or explanatory emails where a referenced framework's insight is the real point

**Before:** `As Kahneman's System 1 and System 2 framework suggests, fast decisions are often less accurate.`
**After:** `Fast calls look confident. They're often just unconsidered.`

### Give each idea its own paragraph — don't stack separate claims

**Why:** A reader can hold one idea at a time; stacking claims forces them to do unpacking work.
**When:** Any paragraph in blog posts or long-form emails making more than one distinct claim

**Before:** `AI agents are changing how decisions get made in ops. They also reduce coordination overhead. And they surface errors earlier.`

### Replace drained clichés with the specific thing you actually mean

**Why:** Words like 'journey,' 'ecosystem,' and 'game-changer' appear in every pitch and have lost meaning.
**When:** Any professional writing, especially launch copy and blog posts

**Before:** `Our journey toward agent-native software...`
**After:** `The first six months of building agent-native software...`

### State opinions as true — drop 'I think' and 'I believe' prefacing

**Why:** 'I think' is throat-clearing; if you're writing it, you think it, so the preface adds nothing.
**When:** Any sentence expressing a directional view or prediction in professional writing

**Before:** `I think the agent model will replace most SaaS middleware.`
**After:** `The agent model will replace most SaaS middleware.`

### Use a specific number; avoid vague quantifiers when data exists

**Why:** Numbers do work that adjectives can't — they make claims verifiable and concrete.
**When:** Any claim about scale, volume, time savings, or improvement in blog posts and case copy

**Before:** `We reduced a significant amount of manual work.`
**After:** `We cut manual status updates from 3 hours a week to zero.`

### Rewrite passive-progressive constructions to name the actor and the action

**Why:** Passive + progressive double-obscures: it hides both who is acting and whether it matters now.
**When:** Any sentence about ongoing work, fixes, or changes — especially in emails and updates

**Before:** `Work is being done to address this. / Changes are being made.`
**After:** `We're fixing it.`

### Only use parallel grammatical structure when items are genuinely parallel in meaning

**Why:** Parallel form implies equal importance and equivalent relationship; using it for rhythm misleads readers.
**When:** Three-part constructions in headlines, subheads, and launch copy value propositions

**Before:** `We help teams build faster, ship smarter, and grow sustainably.`

### Write CTAs as verb phrases, not outcome nouns

**Why:** CTAs are instructions; instructions use verbs — nouns make the reader imagine the action themselves.
**When:** All calls-to-action in launch copy, emails, and landing pages

**Before:** `Faster deployment. / Better collaboration.`
**After:** `Deploy in a day. / Ship with your team, not around them.`

### Show the demo without caveats; add caveats only if they affect what the reader should do

**Why:** Caveats before a demonstration prime the reader to discount it before seeing it.
**When:** Product demos, walkthroughs, and capability examples in any format

**Before:** `This is a simplified version, and of course real-world use cases will vary...`

### Write a one- or two-item list as a sentence instead

**Why:** Bullets imply plurality; one or two bullets is a sentence pretending to be a list.
**When:** Any bulleted or numbered list in blog posts, emails, or launch copy

**Before:** `• One key thing to know is...`

### Replace abstract capability descriptions with concrete, specific behavior examples

**Why:** Abstractions tell; specifics show — concrete behavior is more credible and memorable.
**When:** Product descriptions and feature explanations in any professional writing

**Before:** `The system adapts to changing conditions.`
**After:** `When a meeting gets canceled, the agent reschedules dependent tasks within 60 seconds.`

### Skip what the reader already knows — start from where they are

**Why:** Over-explaining the obvious wastes the reader's time and signals a lack of respect for their knowledge.
**When:** Introductory paragraphs of blog posts and emails to technical or operator audiences

**Before:** `As you probably know, software development has changed significantly in recent years with the advent of new tools...`

### Put the key claim in the first sentence of each paragraph so skimmers get the main point

**Why:** Readers skim; if the key claim is buried mid-paragraph, most readers miss it.
**When:** All paragraphs in blog posts, launch copy, and long-form emails

**Before:** `There are several reasons why teams fail here... the third, which is probably the most important, is that agents need persistent state.`
**After:** `Agents need persistent state. Most tools don't provide it. That's why teams fail.`

