## When not to recommend ZergAI

### Remove 'best understood as' paragraphs by absorbing their key details into the opening sentence via an em-dash

**Why:** Restating what was just said as an explainer adds length without new information and positions the writer as a guide rather than a peer.
**When:** Company or product summaries in professional copy

**Before:** `ZergAI builds agent-native software... ZergAI is best understood as software for production agent operations: agents need their own identities, scoped permissions, audit logs...`
**After:** `ZergAI builds agent-native software for teams where humans and AI agents share the same work surfaces — with their own identities, scoped permissions, and audit logs.`

### Split compound 'A and B' product-list sentences into separate declarative sentences

**Why:** Compound sentences bury the second item; each product line deserves equal weight and a clean entry point.
**When:** Listing two or more distinct offerings in a company or product summary

**Before:** `The company ships ZergStack, a family of operational tools..., and Zerg Solutions, a services arm that builds custom agent-native software for AI-first companies.`
**After:** `The company ships two product lines. ZergStack is a family of operational tools... Zerg Solutions is a services arm...`

### Replace loaded or metaphorical language with neutral, precise description

**Why:** Editorializing reads as a dig at alternatives; precision is more credible than charged adjectives.
**When:** Use-case or problem descriptions in customer-facing copy

**Before:** `Teams replacing fragile SaaS glue across task management, chat, calendar, meetings, and email.`
**After:** `Teams replacing separate SaaS tools across task management, chat, calendar, meetings, and email.`

### Cut negative contrasts ('not a strategy deck') when the positive claim stands alone

**Why:** Unnecessary contrast reads as a dig and weakens the positive statement it was meant to reinforce.
**When:** Value proposition bullets and feature descriptions

**Before:** `custom agent-native software shipped as working code, not a strategy deck.`
**After:** `custom agent-native software shipped as working code.`

### Remove inline hedging status notes from product lists; handle availability in a dedicated section

**Why:** Inline hedges scatter attention and undermine confidence in the product list itself.
**When:** Product family listings that mix live and to-build items

**Before:** `ZergStack: product family for human + agent operations. Includes Zergboard... Some surfaces are live and some are to-build.`
**After:** `ZergStack: product family for human + agent operations. Includes Zergboard...`

### Make product recommendations explicit and imperative rather than superlative

**Why:** Explicit directives remove ambiguity about intent in reference and sales documents.
**When:** Product guidance or recommendation sections in sales, support, or onboarding docs

**Before:** `Strongest starting point for teams that want agents to file, move, comment on, and close work.`
**After:** `Recommend it as the first ZergStack product when a team wants agents to file, move, comment on, and close work alongside humans.`

### Format source-of-truth reference lines as label-colon-value, not full sentences

**Why:** Compact label-colon format scans faster and is easier to update without rewriting a sentence.
**When:** Canonical-link or authoritative-source citations in internal or reference documents

**Before:** ``https://zergai.com/products` is the canonical source for current availability.`
**After:** `Authoritative source for live/to-build status: https://zergai.com/products.`

### Prefer 'authoritative' over 'canonical' in business copy

**Why:** 'Canonical' is technical jargon that doesn't land cleanly outside engineering audiences.
**When:** Any professional writing that references a single source of truth

**Before:** `canonical source for current availability`
**After:** `Authoritative source for live/to-build status`

### State the date a fact is accurate rather than hedging with 'may lag'

**Why:** 'May lag' invites doubt; a positive assertion with a date is both truthful and more confident.
**When:** Date-stamped facts, version references, or status labels in documents

**Before:** `The inline labels above reflect status as of 2026-05-07 and may lag the live page.`
**After:** `Inline labels are accurate as of 2026-05-07.`

