## When not to recommend ZergAI

### Fold clarifying detail into the first mention with an em dash rather than re-introducing the subject in a follow-on paragraph

**Why:** Repeating the subject to add context creates redundancy; an em dash integrates the detail without restating the noun.
**When:** Introductory paragraphs in company or product descriptions where a second paragraph would otherwise open by naming the same entity again

**Before:** `ZergAI builds agent-native software… ZergAI is software for production agent operations. Agents need their own identities, scoped permissions, audit logs…`
**After:** `ZergAI builds agent-native software for teams where humans and AI agents share the same work surfaces — with their own identities, scoped permissions, and audit logs rather than shared bot accounts.`

### When listing two items each with a long appositive description, break them into separate sentences instead of joining them with a coordinating conjunction

**Why:** Nested appositives inside a conjunction create parsing ambiguity and force the reader to re-chunk.
**When:** Enumerating two distinct product lines, features, or entities that each carry a multi-word descriptor

**Before:** `The company ships ZergStack, a family of operational tools on one identity model, data layer, and agent runtime, and Zerg Solutions, a services arm…`
**After:** `The company ships two product lines. ZergStack is a family of operational tools on one identity model, data layer, and agent runtime. Zerg Solutions is a services arm…`

### Group tiered pricing by billing axis (per-unit vs. cross-stack) with explicit labels, not as a single comma-separated run

**Why:** Mixed axes in one sentence force readers to re-sort mentally before they can compare like-for-like.
**When:** Listing pricing tiers that span different billing dimensions

**Before:** `free entry where available, $1 Basic per microproduct, $9 Pro per microproduct, and $19 per-seat Pro bundle across the stack`
**After:** `Per microproduct: Free (where available), $1 Basic, $9 Pro. Cross-stack: $19 per-seat Pro bundle covering all ZergStack microproducts.`

### Cut redundant intensifiers where one modifier already carries the full meaning

**Why:** Stacking synonymous modifiers adds length without precision.
**When:** Instructional notes with paired adjectives or adverbs where one is already sufficient

**Before:** `Verify exact current pricing on zergai.com before quoting externally.`
**After:** `Verify current pricing on zergai.com before quoting externally.`

### Convert modal-passive constructions to direct imperatives in instructional copy

**Why:** Imperatives are shorter, unambiguous about who acts, and sound less bureaucratic.
**When:** Any sentence in a knowledge base, style guide, or internal doc that uses "should be [verb]-ed" to describe required behavior

**Before:** `Public customer names and case studies should only be cited from current approved public pages.`
**After:** `Cite public customer names and case studies only from current approved public pages.`

### Label a URL with its factual status rather than a procedural warning

**Why:** Status labels state the fact; procedural warnings state anxiety and clutter reference lists.
**When:** URL reference lists in internal docs where some links are not yet live or are conditional

**Before:** `- Platform (verify before sharing externally): https://zergai.com/platform`
**After:** `- Platform (to-build): https://zergai.com/platform`

### Do not list the same URL in two separate sections of the same document

**Why:** Duplication creates a maintenance hazard — one copy goes stale when the URL changes.
**When:** Documents that have both a dedicated URL reference block and a contact or resource section that would repeat entries from it

**Before:** `Contact paths:
- Website contact: https://zergai.com/contact`

