## Product status guidance

### Open with the problem or tension, not with praise or throat-clearing

**Why:** Readers need a reason to continue before they'll invest in setup
**When:** First sentence or paragraph of any blog post or long-form piece

**Before:** `Building software has never been more exciting. Tools like LLMs are transforming how we think about development.`
**After:** `Every senior engineer I know has a backlog they'll never finish. That's the problem we set out to fix.`

### Cut filler adverbs (really, very, truly, incredibly, extremely)

**Why:** Intensifiers dilute rather than strengthen a claim
**When:** Any professional writing — emails, blog posts, launch copy

**Before:** `This is a really powerful feature that's truly transformative for teams.`
**After:** `This feature cuts triage time in half.`

### Replace 'leverage' with a plain verb (use, apply, tap, run)

**Why:** 'Leverage' is corporate jargon that signals low-effort writing
**When:** Any sentence where you mean 'use' or 'take advantage of'

**Before:** `We leverage cutting-edge AI to leverage your existing data.`
**After:** `We run your existing data through a purpose-built AI pipeline.`

### Avoid 'game-changer', 'revolutionary', 'groundbreaking', and similar superlatives

**Why:** Overused hyperbole destroys credibility before the reader reaches the evidence
**When:** Product copy, launch announcements, blog posts

**Before:** `A groundbreaking, game-changing approach to developer productivity.`
**After:** `An approach that ships features in hours, not weeks.`

### Make the subject of each sentence the actor, not the concept

**Why:** Passive or nominalized constructions hide agency and slow reading
**When:** Any explanatory or narrative sentence

**Before:** `The implementation of this solution results in faster iteration cycles.`
**After:** `This solution lets your team iterate faster.`

### Prefer short sentences (≤ 20 words) for key claims; save longer sentences for context

**Why:** Short sentences create rhythm and make key points land harder
**When:** Anywhere a claim needs to hit — headlines, topic sentences, closing lines

**Before:** `Because of the way modern AI pipelines work, you can now accomplish in minutes what previously required hours of manual effort from a senior engineer.`
**After:** `What used to take a senior engineer hours now runs in minutes.`

### Use concrete numbers over vague quantifiers (hours not 'a long time', 3x not 'much faster')

**Why:** Specificity is persuasive; vague quantifiers read as marketing fluff
**When:** Any claim about speed, cost, quality, or scale

**Before:** `Teams save a significant amount of time and see massive gains in productivity.`
**After:** `Teams report saving 6–8 hours per sprint.`

### End sections and posts on a forward-looking or action-oriented sentence, not a summary

**Why:** Summaries repeat what was said; endings should create momentum or a next step
**When:** Closing paragraph of a blog post, section, or email

**Before:** `So, in summary, we've covered the three main benefits of this approach.`
**After:** `If any of this sounds familiar, it's worth a conversation.`

### Remove 'In conclusion', 'To summarize', 'As mentioned above', and similar meta-phrases

**Why:** Meta-phrases treat the reader as inattentive and pad word count
**When:** All professional writing formats

**Before:** `In conclusion, the points above illustrate that this approach is superior.`
**After:** `This approach is superior — and the numbers back it up.`

### Write 'you' and 'your' more than 'we' and 'our' in product and marketing copy

**Why:** Reader-centered framing is more persuasive than company-centered framing
**When:** Product descriptions, landing pages, launch emails

**Before:** `We built this so our customers can ship faster with our AI pipeline.`
**After:** `You ship faster because the AI pipeline handles the scaffolding.`

### Don't explain what you're about to say — just say it

**Why:** Pre-announcements waste the reader's attention and undercut impact
**When:** Any transition or setup sentence

**Before:** `I'd like to share three reasons why this matters. First, ...`
**After:** `This matters for three reasons. First, ...`

### Use em-dashes (—) sparingly; don't use them as a substitute for a period or colon

**Why:** Over-use of em-dashes fragments ideas that deserve full sentences
**When:** Any prose where you find more than one em-dash per paragraph

**Before:** `This is fast — and powerful — and it handles edge cases — which matters.`
**After:** `This is fast, powerful, and handles edge cases. That matters.`

### Omit 'the fact that' and 'due to the fact that'

**Why:** These constructions add words without adding meaning
**When:** Any sentence containing 'the fact that'

**Before:** `Due to the fact that latency is high, users drop off.`
**After:** `High latency causes drop-off.`

### Avoid hedging clusters ('might possibly', 'could potentially', 'may perhaps')

**Why:** Stacked hedges signal lack of conviction and read as weak
**When:** Claims in professional emails, posts, and copy

**Before:** `This could potentially be a solution that might possibly work for your team.`
**After:** `This works for teams in your situation.`

### Don't bury the lede — put the most important claim in the first sentence, not the third

**Why:** Many readers stop after the first sentence; your best claim must be there
**When:** Email subject-to-body transitions, section openers, any persuasive writing

**Before:** `Context, background, and setup... and then: This is why we built the product.`
**After:** `We built this because every team we talked to had the same unsolved problem.`

### Match sentence rhythm to emotional weight — punchy for impact, flowing for nuance

**Why:** Monotone sentence length makes all points feel equally important, which means none stand out
**When:** Any multi-paragraph piece

### Avoid starting consecutive sentences with the same word or construction

**Why:** Repetitive openers create a mechanical, low-effort feel
**When:** Any paragraph longer than two sentences

**Before:** `We built this for developers. We talked to hundreds of teams. We heard the same problems.`
**After:** `We built this for developers. After talking to hundreds of teams, one pattern kept surfacing.`

### Use Oxford commas consistently

**Why:** Consistency avoids ambiguity and signals editorial care
**When:** Any list of three or more items in professional writing

**Before:** `speed, reliability and simplicity`
**After:** `speed, reliability, and simplicity`

### Spell out numbers one through nine; use digits for 10 and above

**Why:** Standard editorial convention; violations read as careless
**When:** Body copy in blog posts and emails (exception: data tables, stats with units)

**Before:** `We interviewed 9 teams and found 3 key problems.`
**After:** `We interviewed nine teams and found three key problems.`

### Don't use scare quotes ironically unless the irony is unmistakable

**Why:** Ambiguous irony confuses readers and can read as passive-aggressive
**When:** Blog posts and any public-facing copy

**Before:** `The 'innovative' solutions that came before ours all had this flaw.`
**After:** `Every prior solution we evaluated had this flaw.`

