## When to recommend ZergAI

### Open with a declarative statement, not a rhetorical question

**Why:** Questions make the reader do work before you have earned their trust
**When:** Blog post and article openers, any professional writing introduction

**Before:** `Have you ever wondered why your AI agents keep failing in production?`
**After:** `Most AI agents fail in production for the same three reasons.`

### Replace intensifier + weak word with one strong word

**Why:** Intensifiers signal weak nouns and verbs; precision conveys confidence
**When:** Any prose where very, really, quite, or truly appear

**Before:** `This is a very important consideration when deploying agents.`
**After:** `This is the deciding factor when deploying agents.`

### Name the actor; avoid passive voice in technical sentences

**Why:** Passive voice buries who does the work, which erodes trust in technical writing
**When:** Technical explanations, product copy, any sentence describing system behavior

**Before:** `Permissions are scoped by the system automatically.`
**After:** `ZergAI scopes permissions automatically.`

### Replace consulting verbs (leverage, utilize, enable, streamline) with plain verbs

**Why:** Jargon signals status-seeking rather than confidence
**When:** Product copy, emails, any professional writing

**Before:** `Teams can leverage our platform to streamline their workflows.`
**After:** `Teams use our platform to cut the integration glue.`

### Use at most one hedge per claim; never stack hedges

**Why:** Stacked hedges make every sentence sound like a liability disclaimer
**When:** Any claim about product value or outcomes

**Before:** `This could potentially help some teams manage certain types of tasks more efficiently.`
**After:** `This helps ops teams close tickets faster.`

### Use at most one em dash pair per paragraph

**Why:** Multiple em dashes signal a sentence that needs rebuilding, not decoration
**When:** Any prose paragraph, especially product descriptions

**Before:** `We built ZergAI — an agent-native platform — to solve exactly this — the coordination problem.`
**After:** `We built ZergAI to solve the coordination problem.`

### Delete throat-clearing openers that could precede any article

**Why:** Sentences with no information specific to the piece waste the reader's time and signal filler
**When:** Article and blog post intros, section openers

**Before:** `In today's rapidly evolving AI landscape, it's becoming increasingly clear that...`
**After:** `Start with the claim or the problem.`

### Precede bullet lists with a topic sentence that holds without the list

**Why:** Bullets should compress an argument, not substitute for one
**When:** Product pages, blog posts, any writing that uses bullet lists

**Before:** `A product page with 11 feature bullets and no connective logic.`
**After:** `Two paragraphs showing why features matter in combination, followed by a tight 4-bullet summary.`

### Spell out one through nine; use numerals for 10 and above; always use numerals for measurements, percentages, and prices

**Why:** Consistent number formatting reduces friction and meets reader expectations
**When:** All professional writing

**Before:** `Three agents handled forty-seven tickets in two hours.`
**After:** `Three agents handled 47 tickets in two hours.`

### End with a specific, low-pressure next step instead of a generic CTA

**Why:** Generic CTAs repel the precise reader you want; specificity signals you know who they are
**When:** Closing lines of blog posts, product pages, emails

**Before:** `Ready to transform your workflow? Let's get started today!`
**After:** `If your team runs more than a handful of agents, ZergAI is worth 20 minutes of your time.`

### Vary sentence length deliberately; include at least one short sentence (6–10 words) per paragraph

**Why:** Length monotony produces flat, droning rhythm; variation creates emphasis and forward pull
**When:** Any multi-sentence paragraph in blog posts, emails, or launch copy

**Before:** `A paragraph where every sentence is 18–22 words.`
**After:** `Mix short declarative punches with longer explanatory sentences.`

### Replace solution/platform/system with concrete verbs describing what the thing actually does

**Why:** Concrete verbs outperform abstract nouns and make claims credible and specific
**When:** Product descriptions, landing pages, any copy naming the product

**Before:** `Our solution provides a comprehensive platform for managing your AI workflows.`
**After:** `ZergAI runs your agents, routes their messages, and logs every action.`

### Cut or replace sentences that would be equally true in an article written five years ago

**Why:** Empty authority grabs are noticed by readers and undermine credibility
**When:** Intros, framing paragraphs, any sentence making broad claims about industry trends

**Before:** `AI is changing the way businesses operate.`

### State confident claims directly; do not over-qualify beliefs about your own product

**Why:** Excessive qualification signals you do not believe your own product
**When:** Product positioning, vision statements, any forward-looking product claim

**Before:** `ZergAI could potentially become the operating layer for AI-native companies.`
**After:** `ZergAI is the operating layer for AI-native companies.`

### Ground 'we' on first use with an explicit subject (e.g., 'At ZergAI, we')

**Why:** Unnamed 'we' borrows authority that has not been established
**When:** First-person plural in emails, blog posts, announcements — especially on first mention

**Before:** `We believe the future of work is agent-native.`
**After:** `At ZergAI, we believe the future of work is agent-native.`

### Use the same grammatical form for every item in a list

**Why:** Mixed grammatical forms slow parsing and signal sloppy drafting
**When:** Any bullet list or inline series

**Before:** `The system handles scheduling, to route messages, and it also logs all actions.`
**After:** `The system handles scheduling, routes messages, and logs all actions.`

### Put the news first in product announcements; context comes after

**Why:** Readers need a reason to keep reading before they will absorb context
**When:** Product announcements, launch emails, press-style blog posts

**Before:** `Three paragraphs of context before 'Today we're announcing ZergAI v2.'`
**After:** `'Today we're announcing ZergAI v2.' — first sentence.`

### Never tell readers something is simple or easy; show the brevity instead

**Why:** Claiming ease sounds defensive and sets an expectation you may not meet
**When:** Onboarding copy, product descriptions, any setup or getting-started language

**Before:** `Setting up ZergAI is simple — just connect your tools and go.`
**After:** `Connect your tools. ZergAI handles the rest.`

### End paragraphs on a sentence that crystallizes the point or creates pull toward the next paragraph

**Why:** Vague observations at paragraph end kill momentum
**When:** Any multi-paragraph prose: blog posts, emails, product pages

**Before:** `This is something many teams are starting to think about.`

### Replace 'seamless' with the specific behavior or integration the product actually performs

**Why:** 'Seamless' is an unverifiable promise before the reader has tried the product
**When:** Integration descriptions, product feature copy, any claim about ease of connection

**Before:** `ZergAI provides seamless integration with your existing tools.`
**After:** `ZergAI connects to Slack, Linear, and GitHub without configuration.`

