## 2026-05-09 — to llms

### Strip announcement language and lead with the concrete outcome

**Why:** Readers care about what changed, not the act of announcing it.
**When:** Blog posts and launch copy that open with 'we are excited to announce' or similar

**Before:** `We are excited to announce that we have launched a new feature that allows users to save time by automating their workflow.`
**After:** `We launched a feature that cuts workflow time.`

### Cut throat-clearing openers and get to the ask immediately

**Why:** Preamble delays the point and signals low confidence.
**When:** Professional emails, especially outreach or follow-up

**Before:** `I wanted to reach out to touch base and see if you had a chance to look at the proposal I sent over last week.`
**After:** `Did you get a chance to look at the proposal?`

### Delete meta-commentary like 'it's important to note that'

**Why:** If it's worth saying, just say it — the meta-layer adds no information.
**When:** Any prose register: blog posts, emails, copy

**Before:** `It's important to note that this approach has some limitations.`
**After:** `This approach has limitations.`

### Replace tech-marketing jargon with plain, specific description

**Why:** Jargon obscures meaning and reads as generic; specificity builds trust.
**When:** Launch copy and product descriptions

**Before:** `Our platform leverages cutting-edge AI technology to provide actionable insights that drive business value.`
**After:** `It shows you what's slowing your team down.`

### Delete generic scene-setting openers; start in the action

**Why:** Warm-up sentences waste the reader's attention before earning it.
**When:** Blog post introductions

**Before:** `In today's fast-paced business environment, companies need to adapt quickly to stay competitive.`

### Replace sign-off boilerplate with a direct, one-sentence close

**Why:** Boilerplate closers feel impersonal and inflate word count.
**When:** Email sign-offs

**Before:** `Please don't hesitate to reach out if you have any questions or need any clarification on any of the above.`
**After:** `Questions? Reply here.`

### Delete transitional throat-clearing like 'there are a number of reasons'

**Why:** The transition adds nothing; the reasons that follow speak for themselves.
**When:** Blog posts and structured prose

**Before:** `There are a number of reasons why this matters.`

### Cut persona-targeting preamble and state the functional benefit directly

**Why:** Addressing an imagined persona delays the claim that actually sells.
**When:** Launch copy and product marketing

**Before:** `Designed with the modern professional in mind, our solution seamlessly integrates with your existing tools.`
**After:** `Plugs into the tools you already use.`

### Delete social-filler openers like 'I hope this email finds you well'

**Why:** They are pure noise; no reader wants them.
**When:** Email openings

**Before:** `I hope this email finds you well.`

### Replace 'it is worth mentioning that' with a plain declarative sentence

**Why:** The hedge signals uncertainty without adding useful qualification.
**When:** Blog posts and any explanatory prose

**Before:** `It is worth mentioning that the results may vary depending on the specific use case.`
**After:** `Results vary by use case.`

### Delete generic commitment claims that contain no specifics

**Why:** Unverifiable claims erode credibility rather than building it.
**When:** Launch copy and about/product pages

**Before:** `We are committed to providing our customers with the highest quality experience possible.`

### End on the last substantive point; don't add a restating conclusion

**Why:** Summary conclusions that restate prior content waste the reader's time.
**When:** Blog post endings

**Before:** `In conclusion, we have seen that this approach offers significant advantages over traditional methods.`

### Replace formal attachment language with plain spoken phrasing

**Why:** Formal phrasing creates unnecessary distance in professional correspondence.
**When:** Emails with attachments or linked documents

**Before:** `Attached please find the document I mentioned in our previous conversation.`
**After:** `Here's the doc.`

### Delete vague team or expertise claims without supporting specifics

**Why:** Generic claims signal filler and are ignored by readers.
**When:** Launch copy and marketing pages

**Before:** `Our team of experts is dedicated to helping you achieve your goals.`

### Replace 'it should be noted that' with a direct statement

**Why:** The hedge implies importance without stating what it actually is.
**When:** Blog posts and technical prose

**Before:** `It should be noted that the following examples are simplified for illustrative purposes.`
**After:** `These examples are simplified.`

### Cut epistolary framing like 'I am writing to inform you that'

**Why:** The framing is redundant — the email already implies you are writing.
**When:** Transactional and notification emails

**Before:** `I am writing to inform you that your account has been successfully updated.`
**After:** `Your account is updated.`

### Delete imperative hype phrases; replace with a specific claim or cut entirely

**Why:** Hype without specifics is noise that trained readers skip.
**When:** Launch copy and product headlines

**Before:** `Experience the power of our revolutionary new product.`

### Delete forward-looking filler that doesn't commit to a specific claim

**Why:** Vague future-tense framing defers rather than communicates.
**When:** Blog post transitions and conclusions

**Before:** `As we move forward into the future, it will be increasingly important to consider...`

### Cut 'just wanted to follow up' framing and ask the question directly

**Why:** The apology frame weakens the ask and pads word count.
**When:** Follow-up emails

**Before:** `Just wanted to follow up on my previous email to see if you had any thoughts.`
**After:** `Any thoughts on this?`

### Avoid cliché tech phrases like 'move fast without breaking things' or 'game-changer'

**Why:** Clichés signal low effort and in-group posturing rather than substance.
**When:** Launch copy and any public-facing product writing

**Before:** `Built for teams who want to move fast without breaking things.`

