## 2026-05-09 — to agents-that-remember

### Open with the problem the reader already feels, not a scene-setting summary of how agents work

**Why:** Readers grant attention when they recognize their own pain immediately; background earns its place only after the hook.
**When:** Blog post or technical essay intros where the subject is a well-known AI behavior

**Before:** `AI agents write code by trying, failing, seeing the error, and trying again — often with the same broken approach, slightly rephrased.`
**After:** `The retry loop is the default, and the default is wrong.`

### Name Zerg's stake in the problem before explaining the paper

**Why:** Credibility and relevance land harder when the reader knows the writer has skin in the game.
**When:** Any company blog post covering external research

**Before:** `a new paper from a team across CMU, the University of Washington, and Arm caught our eye`
**After:** `We don't have an analog of this in our own pipeline yet, and that's exactly why this paper jumped out.`

