## The thing agents keep forgetting

### Open with the concrete fact or number, not the framing sentence

**Why:** The lead earns attention; burying the payload in sentence two makes readers work for the point
**When:** First paragraph of any blog post, especially technical posts announcing a result

**Before:** `Most AI agents approach this the same way they approach everything. When generation fails, the agent sees the error and tries again.`
**After:** `Single-pass code correctness jumped from 22% to 54%—before any search, before any optimization.`

### Put the punchline number in the same sentence as its cause, not a paragraph later

**Why:** Separating cause and effect forces re-reading and dilutes impact
**When:** Any paragraph reporting a metric tied to a method or intervention

**Before:** `AdaExplore distilled 1,178 raw failure traces into 78 high-frequency rules. Single-pass correctness jumped from 22% to 54%.`
**After:** `Distilling 1,178 traces into 78 rules pushed single-pass correctness from 22% to 54%.`

### Avoid throat-clearing that names what you are about to say instead of saying it

**Why:** Meta-commentary ('Call it a validity rulebook') substitutes for the actual claim and adds no information
**When:** Any time you catch yourself writing 'Call it X', 'Think of it as Y', or 'In other words'

**Before:** `Call it a validity rulebook: a cross-task memory of what Triton won't tolerate.`
**After:** `The result is a cross-task memory of what Triton won't tolerate—78 rules the agent checks before generating.`

### Collapse the deduplication pipeline description into one crisp sentence with the key numbers only

**Why:** Listing every intermediate step buries the result; readers care about input, method, and output—not every node
**When:** Describing multi-stage data processing pipelines in blog posts or technical summaries

**Before:** `1,178 raw failure traces became 174 unique patterns after deduplication, then 78 high-frequency rules after filtering.`
**After:** `1,178 failure traces, filtered to 78 high-frequency rules.`

### Name what the agent 'doesn't do' only when it directly contrasts with what your system does do

**Why:** Negative framing without an immediate positive payoff reads as a setup without a punchline
**When:** Competitive or contrast framing in blog posts about new approaches

**Before:** `What it doesn't do is ask whether it has seen this class of failure before, and what rule that failure points to.`
**After:** `AdaExplore asks exactly that question—and answers it by mining its own failure history.`

### End section closers with the implication, not the restatement

**Why:** Restating the metric the reader just absorbed is filler; the implication is the value
**When:** Closing sentences of any paragraph that contains a quantitative result

**Before:** `The agent got the code right more than twice as often, because it stopped repeating known mistakes.`
**After:** `Stopping known mistakes was enough to double correctness—before tuning a single hyperparameter.`

