## Modes

### Open with the subject and main verb; cut participial warm-up phrases

**Why:** Participial openers delay the subject and make claims feel hedged rather than direct.
**When:** Blog post and launch copy leads, any sentence that opens with -ing or -ed

**Before:** `Building on years of experience, we designed Zerg to give teams full control.`
**After:** `We designed Zerg to give teams full control.`

### Delete hollow intensifiers such as 'incredibly', 'extremely', 'very', and 'really'

**Why:** These words add no information and signal that the underlying claim needs strengthening, not amplifying.
**When:** All professional writing, especially launch copy and blog posts

**Before:** `Zerg is an incredibly powerful platform for growing teams.`
**After:** `Zerg is a platform built for growing teams.`

### Rewrite agentless passive constructions in active voice

**Why:** Passive without an agent hides who did what and dilutes accountability.
**When:** Any prose where a human or system performed the action

**Before:** `Errors were caught early and the deployment was rolled back.`
**After:** `The team caught errors early and rolled back the deployment.`

### Cut throat-clearing openers that delay the actual claim

**Why:** Readers arrive wanting the point; front-loading meta-commentary wastes their attention.
**When:** Email subject lines, blog post first sentences, launch page H1 and H2

**Before:** `In this post, I want to share some thoughts on why agent memory matters.`
**After:** `Agent memory is what turns a chatbot into a collaborator.`

### Replace nominalizations with the verb form

**Why:** Nominalizations (decision → decide, implementation → implement) add syllables and slow pace.
**When:** Technical blog posts and emails; especially common after 'make a', 'give a', 'have a'

**Before:** `We made the decision to give an implementation of persistent state a try.`
**After:** `We decided to try implementing persistent state.`

### Put the most important information at the end of the sentence, not the middle

**Why:** English readers weight sentence endings; burying the payoff in a subordinate clause loses it.
**When:** Any sentence with a notable claim or number; especially in launch copy and blog conclusions

**Before:** `We shipped, after six months of work on the memory layer, persistent agent context.`
**After:** `After six months on the memory layer, we shipped persistent agent context.`

### Avoid hedging declarative claims with 'I think', 'sort of', 'kind of', or 'arguably'

**Why:** Hedges on factual or confident claims undermine authority; save them for genuine uncertainty.
**When:** Blog posts and launch copy where the claim is intentional, not speculative

**Before:** `This is arguably one of the harder problems in kind of stateful AI design.`
**After:** `This is one of the harder problems in stateful AI design.`

### Use one em-dash per sentence maximum; prefer a period or comma when the aside can stand alone

**Why:** Multiple em-dashes in a sentence fragment attention and signal a sentence that should be split.
**When:** Blog posts; launch copy should use almost none

**Before:** `Agents need memory — persistent, structured memory — not just context windows — to actually grow.`
**After:** `Agents need persistent, structured memory — not just context windows — to actually grow.`

### Keep parallel list items grammatically identical in form

**Why:** Broken parallelism forces readers to re-parse and signals uneven thinking.
**When:** Bullet lists in emails, blog posts, and launch feature lists

**Before:** `• Faster deploys
• Reducing errors
• Your team stays in sync`
**After:** `• Faster deploys
• Fewer errors
• Tighter team sync`

### Lead with the concrete benefit or outcome, not the mechanism or feature

**Why:** Readers care about what changes for them before they care about how it works.
**When:** Launch copy, email subject lines, blog post subheadings

**Before:** `Zerg uses a graph-based task scheduler to coordinate your agents.`
**After:** `Your agents stay coordinated — Zerg's task scheduler handles the rest.`

### Write numbers below ten as words; use numerals for 10 and above

**Why:** Standard editorial convention; mixing the two in a single piece looks inconsistent.
**When:** All professional writing except code, data tables, and UI copy

**Before:** `3 agents failed out of fifteen runs.`
**After:** `Three agents failed out of 15 runs.`

### Avoid starting consecutive sentences with the same word or phrase

**Why:** Repeated sentence openers create a monotonous rhythm that reads like a draft, not a finished piece.
**When:** Blog posts and longer emails; especially noticeable in three-sentence paragraphs

**Before:** `Memory lets agents learn. Memory lets them personalize. Memory lets teams move faster.`
**After:** `Memory lets agents learn, personalize responses, and help teams move faster.`

### Use contractions in conversational registers; avoid them in formal launch or press copy

**Why:** Contractions calibrate warmth and register; misusing them makes the piece feel inconsistently polished.
**When:** Blog posts and emails: use contractions freely. Launch page hero and press releases: avoid them.

**Before:** `Zerg doesn't just store context — it's building a persistent model of your work.`
**After:** `Zerg does not just store context — it builds a persistent model of your work.`

### Cut 'that' when it introduces a noun clause and removal does not cause ambiguity

**Why:** Removing optional 'that' tightens sentences without losing meaning.
**When:** All writing; run a pass specifically looking for 'said that', 'think that', 'know that', 'found that'

**Before:** `We found that teams that shipped faster said that documentation was the bottleneck.`
**After:** `We found teams that shipped faster said documentation was the bottleneck.`

### End blog posts with a forward-looking sentence or question, not a summary restatement

**Why:** Restating the intro at the end makes the piece feel circular; a forward look gives readers somewhere to go.
**When:** Blog post conclusions

**Before:** `In summary, agent memory matters because it lets AI systems learn and persist context over time.`
**After:** `The question isn't whether your agents need memory — it's how long you can afford to wait.`

