## Why this exists

### Cut the announcement opener; start with the claim

**Why:** Meta-sentences that announce what a paragraph will do waste the reader's attention and delay the actual point.
**When:** Opening sentences of blog posts, emails, or any professional prose paragraph

**Before:** `In this post, I want to talk about why most onboarding flows fail users before they even reach the first value moment.`
**After:** `Most onboarding flows fail users before they ever reach a first value moment.`

### Find the real verb and use it; kill nominalizations

**Why:** Turning verbs into -tion/-ment/-ance nouns softens the action and adds words.
**When:** Any prose where verbs have been converted to noun phrases

**Before:** `The implementation of rate limiting resulted in a reduction of error rates.`
**After:** `Rate limiting cut error rates.`

### Give each sentence one idea; split compound value claims

**Why:** Stacking two distinct claims in one sentence dilutes both.
**When:** Launch copy, feature descriptions, marketing prose where 'and' joins two independent value props

**Before:** `Dashboards update in real time and you can share them with your team in one click.`
**After:** `Dashboards update in real time. Share with your team in one click.`

### Let the metaphor work; if you must clarify, show it in action rather than paraphrasing it

**Why:** Explaining a metaphor immediately after introducing it kills the image.
**When:** Any prose using analogies or metaphors

**Before:** `Think of it as a circuit breaker — a mechanism that automatically cuts the connection when load exceeds a safe threshold.`
**After:** `Think of it as a circuit breaker: when load spikes, it cuts the connection before anything melts.`

### Remove adverbs that assert ease (simply, easily, quickly, just); show ease instead

**Why:** Filler adverbs promise ease without proving it and read as hollow marketing language.
**When:** Feature descriptions, onboarding copy, any instructional or marketing prose

**Before:** `You can simply connect your data source and immediately start exploring your metrics.`
**After:** `Connect your data source and start exploring metrics.`

### Replace adjective stacks with a verb that demonstrates the benefit

**Why:** Verbs show what a feature does; adjectives only assert qualities the reader must take on faith.
**When:** Feature descriptions, product copy, headlines

**Before:** `A powerful, flexible querying interface for your data.`
**After:** `Query your data without writing SQL.`

### Use present-tense declaratives for consistent feature behaviors; reserve 'can' for genuine optionality

**Why:** 'Can' implies the feature might not perform the action, which undersells reliable behavior.
**When:** Feature descriptions and technical documentation describing default system behavior

**Before:** `The system can detect anomalies in under 200ms.`
**After:** `The system detects anomalies in under 200ms.`

### Lead with the number; follow with the context that validates it

**Why:** Burying the key metric at the end of a sentence makes readers work to find the point.
**When:** Any sentence that contains a metric, statistic, or quantified result

**Before:** `After analyzing thousands of activation flows across our customer base, we found an 18% lift in completion rates.`
**After:** `18% more users complete activation — measured across thousands of flows.`

### Assert directly; cut 'we believe' and 'we think'

**Why:** Epistemic hedges signal lack of conviction and weaken claims the writer should be willing to own.
