## Data sources (priority order)

### Open with the claim or conclusion, not the setup that led to it

**Why:** Readers scan first; burying the point after context causes them to lose interest before reaching it.
**When:** Any paragraph in a blog post, email, or launch copy where you are building toward a conclusion

**Before:** `We tried a lot of different approaches over the past year. We looked at X, Y, and Z. What we found was that simplicity wins.`
**After:** `Simplicity wins. We tried X, Y, and Z over the past year, and they all pointed the same direction.`

### Cut filler phrases that restate the obvious ('It's worth noting that', 'As you can see', 'It goes without saying')

**Why:** These phrases add length without information and signal low confidence in the sentence that follows.
**When:** All registers — blog posts, emails, launch copy

**Before:** `It's worth noting that this approach cuts build time in half.`
**After:** `This approach cuts build time in half.`

### Use concrete numbers instead of vague intensifiers ('dramatically', 'significantly', 'a lot')

**Why:** Specific numbers are credible; vague intensifiers read as marketing puffery and invite skepticism.
**When:** Any claim about scale, improvement, or impact in blog posts and launch copy

**Before:** `This dramatically improved our conversion rate.`
**After:** `This lifted our conversion rate from 2.1 % to 3.8 %.`

### Avoid hedging qualifiers ('kind of', 'sort of', 'a bit', 'pretty', 'fairly') in professional copy

**Why:** Hedging undermines authority and makes assertions feel tentative; cut or replace with the plain adjective.
**When:** Emails to customers or stakeholders, blog posts, launch copy

**Before:** `We built a pretty solid onboarding flow that's kind of self-serve.`
**After:** `We built a self-serve onboarding flow.`

### Write in active voice; move the actor to subject position

**Why:** Active constructions are shorter, clearer, and attribute responsibility explicitly.
**When:** All professional writing, especially blog posts and launch copy

**Before:** `Errors were caught by the linter before they reached production.`
**After:** `The linter caught the errors before they reached production.`

### Replace 'leverage' with 'use', 'build on', or 'take advantage of'

**Why:** 'Leverage' is overused business jargon that blurs meaning; a plain verb is almost always clearer.
**When:** All registers

**Before:** `We leverage existing infrastructure to keep costs low.`
**After:** `We use existing infrastructure to keep costs low.`

### Don't open emails or posts with 'I wanted to' or 'I'm reaching out to'

**Why:** These phrases front-load the writer's intent instead of the reader's benefit; they slow entry and read as timid.
**When:** Email subject and first sentence; blog post openings

**Before:** `I wanted to share some updates on the launch timing.`
**After:** `Launch is moving to March 14. Here's what changed.`

### Trim 'in order to' down to 'to'

**Why:** 'In order to' is three words doing one word's job; no meaning is lost by cutting.
**When:** All writing

**Before:** `We simplified the API in order to reduce onboarding friction.`
**After:** `We simplified the API to reduce onboarding friction.`

### Prefer short Anglo-Saxon words over Latinate equivalents when both are available

**Why:** Shorter, familiar words move faster and feel less corporate; the reader doesn't have to slow down.
**When:** Blog posts and outbound emails; anywhere voice should feel human

**Before:** `We endeavored to ascertain the root cause of the degradation.`
**After:** `We tried to find the root cause of the slowdown.`

### Break sentences longer than ~25 words into two sentences

**Why:** Long sentences require readers to hold multiple ideas in working memory; splitting them preserves each idea cleanly.
**When:** Blog posts, launch copy, customer emails

**Before:** `Because we ship on a two-week cycle and want to keep quality high, we run a full regression suite before every deploy even though it adds 20 minutes to the pipeline.`
**After:** `We ship on a two-week cycle and run a full regression suite before every deploy. It adds 20 minutes to the pipeline, but keeps quality high.`

### Use em-dashes sparingly — one per paragraph at most — not as a general-purpose connector

**Why:** Overuse of em-dashes fragments sentences and makes prose feel breathless; reserve them for genuine asides.
**When:** Blog posts and long-form emails

**Before:** `We shipped the feature — after months of work — and saw great results — almost immediately.`
**After:** `We shipped the feature after months of work and saw results almost immediately.`

### Don't use scare quotes around standard terms you're comfortable with

**Why:** Scare quotes signal distance or irony; using them on plain terms reads as uncertain or condescending.
**When:** All professional writing

**Before:** `We ran a "growth experiment" to test the hypothesis.`
**After:** `We ran a growth experiment to test the hypothesis.`

### Put the most important word or phrase at the end of the sentence, not the middle

**Why:** The final position in a sentence carries the most cognitive weight; saving the key term for last makes it land harder.
**When:** Blog post body copy and launch copy

**Before:** `Speed, which is the thing users care about most, is what we optimized for.`
**After:** `We optimized for the thing users care about most: speed.`

### Replace 'utilize' with 'use'

**Why:** 'Utilize' technically means to make use of something not intended for that purpose; in general copy it's just a longer 'use'.
**When:** All writing

**Before:** `Teams can utilize this dashboard to track progress.`
**After:** `Teams can use this dashboard to track progress.`

### Don't pad transitions with 'As mentioned above' or 'As we discussed'; just make the logical connection directly

**Why:** Back-references interrupt forward momentum and remind readers they might have missed something.
**When:** Blog posts, multi-section emails

**Before:** `As mentioned above, the bottleneck was in the queue. This led us to rethink the architecture.`
**After:** `The queue bottleneck led us to rethink the architecture.`

### Kill throat-clearing introductions that restate the subject of the email before making the point

**Why:** The recipient already knows the context from the subject line or prior thread; repeating it is wasted words.
**When:** Email, especially follow-ups and status updates

**Before:** `Following up on our conversation about the pricing page redesign, I wanted to share a few thoughts.`
**After:** `Three thoughts on the pricing page redesign:`

### Use parallel grammatical structure in lists and bullet points

**Why:** Inconsistent structure forces readers to re-parse each item; parallelism lets them skim.
**When:** Any bulleted or numbered list in emails, docs, or launch copy

**Before:** `• Faster builds
• Reduces errors
• You save money on CI costs`
**After:** `• Faster builds
• Fewer errors
• Lower CI costs`

### Avoid starting consecutive sentences with 'This'

**Why:** Repetition of 'This' at the sentence start creates a monotonous rhythm and each instance can feel vague.
**When:** Blog posts and longer emails

**Before:** `This changed our approach. This meant we had to rebuild the pipeline. This added two weeks.`
**After:** `This changed our approach — we had to rebuild the pipeline, which added two weeks.`

### Replace 'moving forward' and 'going forward' with a specific time reference or just cut it

**Why:** 'Going forward' is hollow filler; readers want to know when, not that you intend to keep existing.
**When:** Emails and update posts

**Before:** `Going forward, we'll send updates every Friday.`
**After:** `Starting this Friday, we'll send weekly updates.`

### Don't use 'exciting' to describe your own product or feature

**Why:** Self-applied enthusiasm reads as hype; readers decide what excites them — show them something worth being excited about instead.
**When:** Launch copy, product announcements, blog posts

**Before:** `We're excited to announce this exciting new feature.`
**After:** `Today we're shipping X. It does Y in half the time.`

### Keep subject lines under 8 words and front-load the most specific noun

**Why:** Mobile email clients truncate long subjects; the first word determines whether the email gets opened.
**When:** Outbound emails, newsletter subject lines

**Before:** `Subject: Just wanted to share some updates on our latest product release`
**After:** `Subject: March release notes — 3 breaking changes`

### Write 'can't', 'won't', 'don't' instead of 'cannot', 'will not', 'do not' unless the register demands formality

**Why:** Contractions match natural spoken cadence and keep the tone approachable; full forms feel stiff in most product contexts.
**When:** Blog posts, product emails, onboarding copy — not legal docs or formal partner agreements

**Before:** `Users will not be able to access the old dashboard after June 1.`
**After:** `Users won't be able to access the old dashboard after June 1.`

### Cut 'very', 'really', and 'quite' from every sentence without replacement

**Why:** These adverbs weaken the adjective they modify; the plain adjective is almost always stronger.
**When:** All registers

**Before:** `This is a very important change that really affects how you use the product.`
**After:** `This change affects how you use the product.`

### Name the customer or persona in CTAs instead of using 'you'

**Why:** Specific personas make the reader self-select and feel the copy was written for them rather than anyone.
**When:** Landing page CTAs and launch copy targeting a defined audience

**Before:** `Sign up if you want faster deploys.`
**After:** `Sign up if you're an engineering team shipping daily.`

### Use sentence case for headings, not title case, in blog posts and product docs

**Why:** Sentence case reads more naturally inline and matches the conversational tone of most product writing; title case can feel formal or bureaucratic.
**When:** Blog post headings, in-product section headers

**Before:** `How to Set Up Your First Funnel in Five Minutes`
**After:** `How to set up your first funnel in five minutes`

